  <h1>How Pedestrian Accident Claims Work</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>The insurance chain</h2><p>At-fault driver&rsquo;s BIL coverage (minimum $25K–$50K in most states, often more). If limits are exhausted: pedestrian&rsquo;s own UM/UIM coverage. PIP in no-fault states for immediate medical bills. Umbrella policies if the driver has one. Workers&rsquo; comp if the accident occurred during employment.</p>
  <h2>Establishing liability</h2><p>Police report, witness statements, and surveillance video are the primary evidence. Accident reconstruction experts are used in contested liability cases. A traffic signal violation, crosswalk violation, or DUI charge creates strong liability evidence.</p>
  <h2>Damages</h2><p>Medical bills (past and future), lost wages and earning capacity, pain and suffering, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, and permanent disability. Pedestrian accidents often involve life-altering injuries — future care costs can dwarf current medical bills.</p>
  <h2>Settlement process</h2><p>Attorney sends demand to insurer with medical records, bills, and lost wage documentation. Insurer makes offer; attorney negotiates. Most cases settle before filing a lawsuit. Cases involving serious injuries or disputes over liability often require filing suit to get fair offers from insurers.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/what-to-do-after-pedestrian-accident">what to do after a pedestrian accident</a> and <a href="/guides/pedestrian-accident-fault">fault and comparative negligence</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
